values.comment: Parse exactly `n` times with a given parser

values.comment:
Parse a sequence of values with the values parser, each separated by

name: Parser.Char
comment:
Pre-made parsers and helpers to create parsers for characters

@docs charCustomError, char, digit, lower, upper, letter, alphanumeric, space, blankspace, newLine, tab

values.name: alphanumeric
values.comment: Parse an alphanumeric character

values.name: blankspace
values.comment: Parse an space, tab, or newline character

values.name: char
values.comment: Parsers a single character, if it fails with a default ExpectedSymbol problem

values.name: charCustomError
values.comment:
Parsers a single character, if it fails it uses the provided problem.
You'll usually want to use `char` (see below)

This is Useful when you want to descript more detail about a what you were
expecting, or when you want to express something in more natural language like:

    "expected a space"

    instead of `char`s default of

    "expected \" \""

values.name: letter
values.comment: Parse a lowercase character parser

values.name: lower
values.comment: Lowercase character parser

values.name: newLine
values.comment: Parse an newline character

values.name: space
values.comment: Parse an space character

values.name: tab
values.comment: Parse an tab character

values.name: upper

name: Parser

types.name: Problem
types.comment: Possible errors that can be encountered while parsing

values.name: andThen
values.comment: Transfrom a parser, based on the result of the previous one
values.type: (resultA -> Parser.Parser resultB) -> Parser.Parser resultA -> Parser.Parser resultB

values.name: fail
values.comment: Fails a parse operation with a problem

values.name: item
values.comment: Parses a single character, always successful as long at the offset is valid

values.name: lazy
values.comment:
Used to declare a parser in an anonymous function, allowing you to defined
resusive grammers

values.name: map
values.comment: Transform the result of a parser

values.name: map2
values.comment: Transform the reuslt of two parser
values.type: (valueA -> valueB -> valueC) -> Parser.Parser valueA -> Parser.Parser valueB -> Parser.Parser valueC

values.name: oneOf
values.comment:
Test a list of parser on a state, without backtracking if a parser fails.
In the case of

    let
        state =
            { source = "bonasdf"
            , offset = 0
            , row = 0
            , col = 0
            }
    in
        oneOf [word "bonjour", lower] state

The parser will fail because it starts to correctly parse "bonjour", but fails
part way. Becuase there is no backtracking, and does not revert to `lower` after
`word "bonjour" fails.

values.name: oneOfBacktrack
values.comment:
Test a list of parser on a state, WITH backtracking if a parser fails. This
means if the first parser fails, it WILL to back to the beginning and try the
next parser
|

values.name: run
values.comment: Wrap a source string into a default state
values.type: Parser.Parser a -> String -> Result.Result ( Parser.State, Parser.Problem ) a

values.name: satisfy
values.comment:
Tests a the parsed character with the function provided, if it return false,
then fail with the provided problem

values.name: succeed
values.comment: Lift a value into a successful parse operation
Given a parserA and parserB, run both but only keep the result from parserB
values.type: Parser.Parser keep -> Parser.Parser ignore -> Parser.Parser keep

values.comment:
Given a parserA that contians a function and parserB that is regular run
both. Apply the result from parserB to the function from parserA
values.type: Parser.Parser (a -> b) -> Parser.Parser a -> Parser.Parser b
